RECOMMENDATION:

  1. Accept the voluntary surrender of the charter of San Diego Cooperative Charter School 2, effective June 30, 2018, and approve a material revision to the charter of San Diego Cooperative Charter School, to add a new location at 3550 Logan Avenue, San Diego, CA, 92113, effective July 1, 2018.

  2. Conduct public hearing on general waiver request to the State Board of Education regarding a portion of Education Code Section 47652; and adopt resolution authorizing submittal of the waiver request to the State Board of Education.

BACKGROUND: San Diego Cooperative Charter School (SDCCS) and San Diego Cooperative Charter School - 2 (SDCCS2) are operated by the nonprofit public benefit corporation, The Theresa Hessling Charter School Project, pursuant to Education Code section 47604. SDCCS2’s original charter petition was approved in December 2012 for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2013, and ending June 30, 2018. The charter term for SDCCS expires on June 30, 2022. SDCCS will submit renewal documents during the 2021-22 school year, at which time the school will be reviewed for renewal.[1]

 

[1] For academic renewal purposes, the SBAC/CAASPP scores from 2016-17 and 2017-18 for SDCCS and SDCCS2 will be combined and averaged. These combined scores will be used as the baseline scores from which academic progress will be measured for the remainder of the charter term.

 

SDCCS2 currently serves Grades K-8 on a co-located (Emerson/Bandini) district site at 3550 Logan Avenue, San Diego, CA, 92113, which falls within the attendance boundaries of Memorial Preparatory Middle, and San Diego High School. The table below provides an overview of SDCCS2.

BOARD REQUESTED ITEMS
 

At the October 3, 2017 meeting, board members requested that future board items include additional information regarding demographic data, facilities, what unique or innovative features the charter school adds to the educational system, and/or how the charter school impacts the overall ecosystem of district and charter schools. The following information is included in response to this request.

                                    

In the 2017-18 school year, about 76.8% of SDCCS2’s enrollment is made up of SDUSD resident students, consisting primarily of students that would have otherwise attended the schools identified in the following table. Other schools serving Grades K-8 in the geographic area near SDCCS2 include King Chavez Arts Academy, King Chavez Athletics Academy, and King Chavez Academy of Excellence.  In total, SDCCS2 has 66 students (21.6%) enrolled that would have been resident students of its closest neighboring (Emerson/Bandini, Baker, Rodriguez) district schools. It is noted that SDCCS2 students come from 53 different district elementary schools, and 12 district middle schools.

In its charter petition, SDCCS2 states that it serves a diverse student population and offers a comprehensive program with a foundation in progressive education which fosters the development of the whole child. The educational program is based on a constructivist model, with students organized in multi-age classrooms, and a focus on Project Based Learning. The school offers a strong social-emotional foundation, is committed to developing a deep family engagement, has implemented schoolwide restorative practices and trauma-informed practices.

 

“There is authentic engagement around issues of social justice, civil discourse, and civic engagement.”  SDCCS2 is a designated Ashoka Changemaker school, part of a global community of schools that prioritize empathy, teamwork, leadership, problem-solving, and changemaking as critical student outcomes. The school has implemented a Readiness to Learn scale to identify barriers to learning. SDCCS2 indicated that families reported being drawn to the school for the social-emotional foundations, philosophical alignment, hands-on learning, trauma-informed practices, and innovative methods in the interest of positive results. 

 

**END SECTION**

 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement, if any.

 

This is the final year of the initial charter term for SDCCS2. During its first term, SDCCS2 had solid operational plans and finances. A single governing board, which is experienced and actively engaged, is responsible for the oversight of both schools. As part of the district’s oversight duties, staff has conducted annual site visits at SDCCS2 which include document review, classroom observations, and interviews of charter board members, teachers, administrators, financial managers, parents, and/or students.

 

Although SDCCS2 has been solid operationally and financially, it has not shown schoolwide academic progress on State assessments, and has had very limited growth in only two of its student subgroups in math, as reflected in the following tables. District staff met with SDCCS2’s leadership to discuss the academic concerns. The school has acknowledged its lack of academic achievement on State assessments, and understands the district’s concerns as they relate to a charter renewal. As a result of these discussions, it was determined that SDCCS2 would not seek to renew its charter, and would instead request to revise the SDCCS charter and operate as a SDCCS school. The decision was based in part on the following factors.

 

  • Both schools share the same governance board.

  • Both schools share the same finance/budget representative.

  • Both schools have solid operational backgrounds.

  • SDCCS has been in operation since 2002, and is academically stable.

  • Merging the schools will provide the Mountain View site with additional resources and structure, which may help improve academic achievement.

  • The schools already participate jointly on some events, such as the California Healthy Kids Survey and some Professional Development.

     

To complete the change, a revision to add a site will be made to the SDCCS charter. In addition, by April 6, 2018, SDCCS will submit to the district clarifications within its existing charter petition regarding Admission Requirements (lottery preferences and procedures), and the Suspension/Expulsion Process.

 

Pursuant to Education Code section 33050, a school district, after a public hearing, may request on behalf of one of its charter schools, that the State Board of Education waive the application of the Education Code and/or the California Code of Regulations. As of June 30, 2018, the SDCCS2 charter will expire and no further funding for the charter school will be provided by the state. There is no technical process to formally merge the schools. The existing Education Code language limits SDCCS' eligibility for receiving an advance apportionment. In order to maintain a funding source for the merger, SDCCS is seeking the approval of the Governing Board of the San Diego Unified School District to request a general waiver from the State Board of Education. The waiver will allow, for the 2018-19 school year, the calculation that would be provided with the special 20-day apportionment, resulting in SDCCS receiving a special advance payment on the full amount of ADA rather than waiting until February when the P-1 reporting period payments start. SDCCS is seeking to waive a portion of California Education Code section 47652, as shown below:

 

(a) Notwithstanding Section 41330, a charter school in its first year of operation shall be eligible to receive funding for the advance apportionment based on an estimate of average daily attendance for the current fiscal year, as approved by the local educational agency that granted its charter and the county office of education in which the charter-granting agency is located. For charter schools approved by the state board, estimated average daily attendance shall be submitted directly to, and approved by, the department. Not later than five business days following the end of the first 20 schooldays, a charter school receiving funding pursuant to this section shall report to the department its actual average daily attendance for that first month, and the Superintendent shall adjust immediately, but not later than 45 days, the amount of its advance apportionment accordingly.

 

(b) In addition to funding received pursuant to Section 41330, a charter school in its second or later year of operation also shall be eligible to receive an advance apportionment pursuant to the process and conditions described in subdivision (a) in any year in which the charter school is adding at least one grade level. The average daily attendance funded for a new grade level shall not exceed the portion of the certified average daily attendance at the second principal apportionment for the prior year that was attributable to pupils in the highest grade served by the charter school.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.

 

Per Education Code section 47607(b), a charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school.
  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years.
  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.
  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.
  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(g).

 

Assembly Bill (AB) 484 amended Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 through 2016-17 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  1. The most recent API calculation;
  2. An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or
  3. Alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups. The decision to use one of these criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

 

SDCCS2 began operating in 2013, the first year that the API testing was suspended, and therefore does not have any historical API or decile ranking data. The only applicable renewal criteria are those that consider comparison data and alternative measures. As a result, the academic analysis is limited to SBAC/CAASPP data, comparison school data, and alternative measures data.

Schoolwide SBAC data indicates that SDCCS2 had significant declines in both ELA and Math over a two-year period (52.7% and 69.2% respectively). In contrast, the majority of the comparison schools had significant increases in ELA and Math over this same time period.

 

Results for the 2014-15 ELA SBAC assessment indicate that SDCCS2 outperformed nine of its comparison schools. The following year SDCCS2 outperformed eight of the comparison schools. In 2016-17, all of the comparison schools outperformed SDCCS2. Results for the 2014-15 Math SBAC assessment indicate that SDCCS2 outperformed or matched six of its comparison schools. The following two years all of the comparison schools outperformed SDCCS2.

SBAC data results by subgroup are mixed. Depending on the subgroup, the school had declines in ELA over a one-year period (subgroup data is not available for 2014-15 based on the small number of students tested), ranging from 24.9% - 49.1%. In Math, the school had increases (388% and 224%) in two subgroups, and a decline of 52.4% in another.

 

To show academic progress, SDCCS2 submitted data based on the SBAC/CAASPP, Northwest Evaluation Association’s Measures of Academic Progress (“MAP”), and Fountas and Pinnell assessments that the school utilized, as well as English Learner reclassification rates. It is noted that the majority of the data provided by the school included results for cohorts, and did not include schoolwide and subgroup data, and/or the data was for only a one-year period. The following data tables were provided by SDCCS2.

The school reported that of its 53 returning EL students in 2017-18, thirteen of them were reclassified, representing a reclassification rate of 24.5% among the returning students.

 

As part of the charter renewal analysis, district staff considered the petition submitted by SDCCS2, the information above, academic and other data available from the State, annual site visits, and the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations, and future plans for improvement. Pursuant to California Ed Code, the charter granting authority is required to consider increases in student academic achievement for all groups of students served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.

 

After a thorough review and analysis, district staff determined that the school’s results on State assessments, and the comparison school data, did not satisfy the academic renewal criteria. The school presented data that reflected increases in academic achievement within cohort groups, and there was very limited growth in two subgroups in SBAC math results. However, staff determined that these reported growths were not enough to satisfy the statutory requirement of showing increases in academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups.

 

This determination by staff led to the previously mentioned conversations with the school’s leadership, and the resulting recommendation that SDCCS2 would not seek to renew its charter, and would instead request to operate as a SDCCS school.

FINANCES

 

District staff reviewed and analyzed the four-year budget and four-year cash flow submitted by SDCCS2, as well as previously submitted financial reports including, but not limited to, the 2016-17 unaudited actuals report, and the 2017-18 preliminary budget.

 

Annual revenues and expenditures are identified by source. Revenue assumptions relate to the applicable state and federal funding formulas. LCFF revenues presented are within range of district staff’s calculations. Expenditures are reasonable and consistent with prior years. SDCCS2 is projected to have operational surpluses of $81,293.00, $197,805.00, $213,866.00, and $247,523.00 in fiscal years 2017-18 through 2020-21, respectively. The ending net position each year meets the district’s minimum reserve requirement of the greater of 3% of expenditures or $50,000.00.

 

Per the fiscal year 2015-16 audit report, SDCCS2’s net assets decreased by $1,651.00 with ending net assets of $151,380.00 which met the District’s reserve requirement. Based on the fiscal year 2016-17 unaudited actuals report, the school reported an operational surplus of $67,274.00 and total net assets of $218,654.00. As of June 30, 2017, available cash of $446,943.00 was sufficient to satisfy current liabilities of $228,290.00.

 

CONCLUSION

 

District staff recommends that the board:

  1. Accept the voluntary surrender of the charter of San Diego Cooperative Charter School 2, effective June 30, 2018, and approve a material revision to the charter of San Diego Cooperative Charter School, to add a new location at 3550 Logan Avenue, San Diego, CA, 92113, effective July 1, 2018.

  2. Conduct public hearing on general waiver request to the State Board of Education regarding a portion of Education Code Section 47652; and adopt resolution authorizing submittal of the waiver request to the State Board of Education.

 

The charter renewal documents submitted by SDCCS2 are attached, as well as a letter from the SDCCS board reflecting its approval of the surrender of the SDCCS2 charter and the revision to the SDCCS charter to add a location.

E. OPERATIONAL MATTERS RESERVED FOR THE BOARD
Subject
4. Public Hearing to Consider Charter Petition to Establish a New Charter School: National University Academy 1001 STEAM
Meeting
Feb 6, 2018 - Regular Charter Meeting, 5:00 P.M.
Type
Information, Public Hearing

RECOMMENDATION: Conduct a public hearing to consider the level of support for the petition to establish National University Academy 1001 STEAM.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: The public hearing is held pursuant to Education Code section 47605 to consider the level of support by teachers employed by the district, other employees of the district, and parents and guardians for the petition to establish a new charter school, National University Academy 1001 STEAM (NUA). Kimberleigh Kopp is the Lead Petitioner.

 

NUA is currently authorized by Lakeside Union School District and serves grades 6-12 at a non-district facility located at 3678 Aero Court, 92123, which is located within the attendance boundaries of Angier Elementary, Taft Middle School, and Kearny High School.

 

NUA proposes to be authorized by San Diego Unified School District as of July 1, 2018, and is requesting a five-year term beginning July 1, 2018, and ending June 30, 2023. The table below summarizes the projected enrollment.

On page 38 of the petition, the school has indicated that its students come from 22 zip codes within San Diego Unified School Districts boundaries. The majority of the students come from the following areas: Oak Park (10.78%), Linda Vista (20.58%), Clairemont (7.84%), Kearny Mesa (14.70%) and Mira Mesa (15.68%).

 

Regarding the educational program, the petition for NUA describes a non-classroom-based educational program with a STEAM focus. The petition states:

  1. At the center of NUAs education philosophy and program are its core values of Innovation, Opportunity, Achievement, Collaboration and Flexibility (Petition at page 27).

     

  2. NUAs program includes site-based independent study and online support (Petition at page 24).

     

  3. NUAs STEAM-focused program is supported by professors from National Universitys School of Engineering and Computing (Petition at page 21).

     

The NUA governing board is the decision-making body for the charter school. The schools bylaws require a minimum of eight and maximum of fifteen governing board members. There are currently seven governing board members, as summarized in the following table.

District staff is reviewing the charter petition documents submitted by NUA, and will bring a recommendation to grant or deny the charter petition at a subsequent date.
